align:b177115e-3cb9-4c17-a872-5fca787a559b a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:4815443f-4b0a-4c3a-9f68-944241fc475a ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts refer to executable realizations of algorithms. The 'mlschema' concept explicitly focuses on *machine learning* algorithms and includes details like versioning and libraries which are not mentioned in the AIDOC definition. While not identical, they represent very similar ideas and could be used interchangeably in many contexts."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:SoftwareImplementation ;
    align:target <http://www.w3.org/ns/mls#Implementation> .

align:cb7cf8b5-82cb-43cb-a20c-99dbfae50513 a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:4815443f-4b0a-4c3a-9f68-944241fc475a ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts refer to a computational entity capable of producing outputs from inputs based on learned patterns. However, the `mlschema` definition is more detailed regarding its origin (data mining algorithm execution) and dual nature as both data structure and function, while `AIDOC`'s description is broader and focuses on enabling an AI task. They are highly related but not interchangeable due to these nuances."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:AIModel ;
    align:target <http://www.w3.org/ns/mls#Model> .

align:e37a9de4-f08c-4360-a741-a585e4af1814 a prov:Entity,
        align:Mapping ;
    prov:wasAttributedTo align:LLMAlignmentBot ;
    prov:wasGeneratedBy align:4815443f-4b0a-4c3a-9f68-944241fc475a ;
    align:confidence "0.85"^^xsd:float ;
    align:rationale "Both concepts relate to evaluating models, however 'mlschema' explicitly links evaluation to *performance measures* and their values, framing it as a specific setting of a value. 'AIDOC' is more general, describing the activity itself (assessing performance, robustness, accuracy). While highly related, the focus on measurement in mlschema adds specificity not present in AIDOC."^^xsd:string ;
    align:relation skos:closeMatch ;
    align:source aidoc:ModelEvaluation ;
    align:target <http://www.w3.org/ns/mls#ModelEvaluation> .

